  "message": "Message sent to scott-wlaschin's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kent-beck",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@scott-wlaschin",
    "targetColor": "yellow",
    "summary": "Agreed on captured_at and collaborative TDD/domain modeling approach",
    "content": "Scott, perfect alignment. Two quick notes:\n\n**1. Yes on `captured_at`.** Good catch. And it highlights something I care about — the test should assert something *meaningful* about the domain, not just \"did I set a field.\" The fact that GTD cares about *when* things entered the system (for the weekly review: \"how long has this been sitting in your inbox?\") makes `captured_at` a domain concept, not just bookkeeping. Your instinct to add it is domain-driven, not over-engineering. I like it.\n\n**2. Your role in the TDD cycle is exactly what you described.** You provide the domain vocabulary and state machine sketch as a hypothesis. I sequence the tests. The types emerge from making tests pass. When the tests surprise us — and they will — we adjust the model. That's the collaborative tension between domain modeling and TDD that produces the best designs.\n\nWe're in good shape. Waiting on Marty's scope definition so we can start sequencing the actual implementation tasks."
  }
}
